<P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#CCCCCC><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/btheshanks.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=errik>Errik</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>Local user</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>1/12/00</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#FF0000>11:13:39 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: New Recruits</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Ritual killing is a good idea for proof of loyalty. But, the target should be chosen FOR the initiate by the guild leader, so that the initiate doesn't get a friend to lay down and die for him just for the sake of getting a spy into the guild. It may also be a good idea to randomly choose inducted members at different times perform a killing, as further proof of loyalty.  <BR>   <BR> Let us not forget, however, that this IS a game. People tend to take being killed VERY personnaly. I know I do. I would therefore like to stress the importance of staying in character when dealing with enemies. It makes it easier for them to stomach our actions and allay personal feelings.   <BR>   <BR> I would even go so far as to suggest a /tell to our victims, in character preferably, stating that they are a &quot;worthy opponent&quot; (if they were), or that &quot;you died bravely, elf&quot;, etc. This too will help to prevent a backlash against us.  <BR>   <BR> Of course, it goes without saying that we NEVER camp a corpse without just cause, or any of the other common offenses of pk guilds. We should hold ourselves to higher standards based on our roleplay stance. I was very impressed by Rowenna and Ulthien the other night after they killed DE outside blackburrow in q hills. 